13:["$","h2","8",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"What Is Base-Rover RTK?"}]]}]
14:["$","p","10",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK is the traditional local correction workflow. One receiver is set as a base station at a known or measured point. Another receiver works as the rover. The base sends correction data to the rover by radio, network or another communication method. The rover applies the correction to calculate a precise position."}]]}]
15:["$","p","12",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK is common in surveying, construction staking, land development and field projects where a team controls both the base and rover. It is relatively simple to understand and can work well when the baseline distance, radio environment and jobsite conditions are suitable."}]]}]
16:["$","h3","14",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Advantages of Base-Rover RTK"}]]}]
17:["$","p","16",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK gives the field team direct control. The crew can set up the base near the project, manage the correction source and continue working even where public correction services are not available. It can be practical for remote areas, temporary sites or projects that do not justify a permanent network."}]]}]
18:["$","p","18",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"It also keeps the system relatively independent. If mobile data coverage is poor, radio correction may still be possible. For contractors who move from site to site, a portable base-rover kit can be a flexible investment."}]]}]
19:["$","h3","20",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Limitations of Base-Rover RTK"}]]}]
1a:["$","p","22",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"The main limitation is coverage. Radio range depends on terrain, antenna height, transmit power, interference and legal frequency rules. The field crew also needs time to set up the base, confirm coordinates, manage power and protect the equipment."}]]}]
1b:["$","p","24",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For large regions or many simultaneous users, one local base can become inefficient. If multiple teams or machines work across a wide area, a network-based correction solution may be more scalable."}]]}]
1c:["$","h2","26",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"What Is a CORS Network?"}]]}]
1d:["$","p","28",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"CORS stands for Continuously Operating Reference Station. A CORS network uses permanent GNSS reference stations installed at fixed locations. These stations collect GNSS data continuously and send it to a data center or correction platform. Users receive correction data through network communication, typically by NTRIP."}]]}]
1e:["$","p","30",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"A CORS network is useful when many users need corrections across a region. It can serve surveyors, GIS teams, agriculture equipment, construction projects, monitoring applications and other positioning services."}]]}]
1f:["$","h3","32",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Equipment in a CORS Setup"}]]}]
20:["$","p","34",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"A practical CORS station may include:"}]]}]
21:["$","ul","ul-18",{"children":[["$","li","0",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"a high-precision GNSS receiver"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"a stable GNSS antenna, often a choke ring antenna for better multipath suppression"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"antenna cable and mounting hardware"}]]}],["$","li","3",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"power supply or backup power"}]]}],["$","li","4",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"network communication equipment"}]]}],["$","li","5",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"lightning protection and enclosure"}]]}],["$","li","6",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"correction software or platform"}]]}],["$","li","7",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"monitoring and maintenance process"}]]}]]}]
22:["$","p","45",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For long-term installations, antenna stability and site selection are critical. A good reference station location should have a stable foundation, open sky view, low multipath and reliable power/network access."}]]}]
23:["$","h2","47",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"What Is VRS?"}]]}]
24:["$","p","49",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"VRS stands for Virtual Reference Station. It is a type of network RTK technology. Instead of sending correction data from only one physical base station, the system uses multiple reference stations in a region to generate correction data that behaves like a virtual base station near the rover. This can improve user experience across a network area."}]]}]
25:["$","p","51",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"VRS is commonly used where a service provider or organization wants to support many users with consistent correction access. It requires GNSS reference stations, software algorithms, data processing, network communication and service management."}]]}]
26:["$","h2","53",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"CORS/VRS vs Base-Rover RTK: Key Comparison"}]]}]
27:["$","h3","55",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Coverage"}]]}]
28:["$","p","57",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK is suitable for a local project area. Coverage depends on radio or network communication from the base. CORS/VRS is designed for wider regional coverage and multiple users."}]]}]
29:["$","p","59",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"If your project is a single construction site or a temporary survey, base-rover may be enough. If your business needs to support many survey teams, agriculture machines or regional users, CORS/VRS is more scalable."}]]}]
2a:["$","h3","61",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Setup Time"}]]}]
2b:["$","p","63",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK requires base setup for each project or jobsite. The crew must place the base, configure it, manage coordinates and power, then connect the rover."}]]}]
2c:["$","p","65",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"CORS/VRS requires more initial infrastructure work, but once the system is running, users can connect more quickly without setting a local base for every job."}]]}]
2d:["$","h3","67",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Accuracy and Stability"}]]}]
2e:["$","p","69",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Both methods can support high-precision positioning when properly deployed. Accuracy depends on receiver quality, antenna quality, correction quality, baseline distance, satellite geometry, multipath and environment."}]]}]
2f:["$","p","71",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For CORS/VRS, station placement, network geometry, data processing and system maintenance are important. For base-rover RTK, local setup, baseline distance and radio/network conditions are important."}]]}]
30:["$","h3","73",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Cost Structure"}]]}]
31:["$","p","75",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK often has a lower initial infrastructure cost for a small team. It requires at least a base and rover kit, accessories and field software."}]]}]
32:["$","p","77",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"CORS/VRS requires higher initial planning and infrastructure investment. However, for many users or long-term regional service, it can reduce repeated base setup and provide scalable access."}]]}]
33:["$","h3","79",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Management Requirements"}]]}]
34:["$","p","81",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK is managed by field crews. CORS/VRS is managed as infrastructure. It may need remote monitoring, server resources, user accounts, correction service management, station maintenance and technical support."}]]}]
35:["$","h2","83",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Which Setup Fits Which Application?"}]]}]
36:["$","h3","85",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Surveying and Mapping Companies"}]]}]
37:["$","p","87",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Small or medium surveying teams may start with base-rover RTK because it is flexible and easier to deploy. If the company regularly works across a city or region and wants faster field access, CORS/VRS can improve efficiency."}]]}]
38:["$","h3","89",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Construction and Engineering Projects"}]]}]
39:["$","p","91",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For a single construction site, base-rover RTK can be sufficient. For large infrastructure projects, road networks, municipal surveying or multiple crews, a CORS or network RTK approach may reduce setup time and improve management."}]]}]
3a:["$","h3","93",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Deformation Monitoring"}]]}]
3b:["$","p","95",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Monitoring projects may need fixed reference stations, stable antennas, continuous data and reliable power. A CORS-style setup is often more suitable than a temporary base. For dam, bridge, slope or building monitoring, installation preparation and long-term stability matter more than quick field mobility."}]]}]
3c:["$","h3","97",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Precision Agriculture"}]]}]
3d:["$","p","99",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Agriculture operations can use either local base correction or network correction. A farm may use a local base station, while an agriculture service provider or dealer may need CORS/VRS to support many machines across a region. Mobile coverage, machine density and service model are important decision factors."}]]}]
3e:["$","h3","101",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"GIS and Public Infrastructure"}]]}]
3f:["$","p","103",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"GIS teams collecting asset data across a city may benefit from network correction if coverage is reliable. This reduces the need to carry and set up a base for each task."}]]}]
40:["$","h2","105",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Installation Preparation Checklist"}]]}]
41:["$","p","107",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Before choosing a correction system, prepare the following information:"}]]}]
42:["$","p","109",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"1. Project area size and terrain"}]]}]
43:["$","p","110",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"2. Number of users or machines"}]]}]
44:["$","p","111",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"3. Required positioning accuracy"}]]}]
45:["$","p","112",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"4. Typical working environment and sky visibility"}]]}]
46:["$","p","113",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"5. Mobile data coverage"}]]}]
47:["$","p","114",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"6. Local radio frequency rules"}]]}]
48:["$","p","115",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"7. Need for permanent stations or temporary setup"}]]}]
49:["$","p","116",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"8. Power and network conditions at station sites"}]]}]
4a:["$","p","117",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"9. Existing receiver, antenna and software compatibility"}]]}]
4b:["$","p","118",{"className":"numbered-line","children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"10. Need for user account management or service billing"}]]}]
4c:["$","p","120",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"This information helps a manufacturer or solution provider recommend the right product mix. It also prevents underestimating installation and maintenance requirements."}]]}]
4d:["$","h2","122",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Mid-Article CTA"}]]}]
4e:["$","p","124",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Planning a CORS/VRS project or comparing it with a local base-rover setup? Send your project area, number of users, target accuracy and application details. TOKNAV can help outline a suitable GNSS correction solution."}]]}]
4f:["$","p","126",{"children":[["$","strong","0",{"children":"CTA Button:"}],["$","span","1",{"children":" Request Solution Proposal"}]]}]
50:["$","p","127",{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Suggested Link: "}],["$","$L12",null,{"href":"/inquiry","children":"/inquiry"}]]}]
51:["$","h2","129",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Factory Testing and Shipment Inspection"}]]}]
52:["$","p","131",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For CORS/VRS and base station equipment, factory testing should go beyond power-on checks. A practical inspection may include:"}]]}]
53:["$","ul","ul-68",{"children":[["$","li","0",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"receiver power and boot test"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"GNSS signal tracking check"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"data output format confirmation"}]]}],["$","li","3",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"network port and communication test"}]]}],["$","li","4",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"antenna cable and connector inspection"}]]}],["$","li","5",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"power adapter and backup power check"}]]}],["$","li","6",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"firmware version confirmation"}]]}],["$","li","7",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"accessory and packing list verification"}]]}]]}]
54:["$","p","142",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For permanent station projects, shipment inspection should also confirm mounting components, antenna model, cable length, enclosure and lightning protection requirements if included in the order."}]]}]
55:["$","h2","144",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Common Procurement Questions"}]]}]
56:["$","h3","146",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Can one base station support many rovers?"}]]}]
57:["$","p","148",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Yes, depending on the communication method, correction format, distance and project setup. However, radio range and user management must be considered. For many users over a wide region, CORS/VRS is usually more scalable."}]]}]
58:["$","h3","150",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Is VRS always more accurate than base-rover RTK?"}]]}]
59:["$","p","152",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Not always. Both can be accurate when properly designed. VRS can improve regional usability, but system design, station geometry, data processing and network reliability matter."}]]}]
5a:["$","h3","154",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Do I need a choke ring antenna for CORS?"}]]}]
5b:["$","p","156",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"For high-precision reference stations, a choke ring antenna is often recommended because it helps reduce multipath and improve phase center stability. The final selection depends on project accuracy, site environment and budget."}]]}]
5c:["$","h3","158",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Can a CORS/VRS system be built step by step?"}]]}]
5d:["$","p","160",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Yes. Some organizations start with a limited number of reference stations and expand as user demand grows. Planning should still consider future coverage and system architecture."}]]}]
5e:["$","h3","162",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"What information is needed for a quotation?"}]]}]
5f:["$","p","164",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Provide the project location, coverage area, number of stations, number of users, application type, power/network conditions and expected correction service workflow."}]]}]
60:["$","h2","166",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"FAQ"}]]}]
61:["$","h3","168",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"What is the difference between CORS and VRS?"}]]}]
62:["$","p","170",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"CORS refers to continuously operating reference stations. VRS is a network RTK technique that generates a virtual reference station near the user based on a reference station network."}]]}]
63:["$","h3","172",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"When should I choose base-rover RTK?"}]]}]
64:["$","p","174",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Choose base-rover RTK for local, temporary or remote projects where you need direct control of the correction source and do not require a regional service network."}]]}]
65:["$","h3","176",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"When should I choose CORS/VRS?"}]]}]
66:["$","p","178",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Choose CORS/VRS when multiple users, wide-area coverage, continuous service or infrastructure-level correction access is required."}]]}]
67:["$","h3","180",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"What receiver is used in a CORS station?"}]]}]
68:["$","p","182",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"A high-precision GNSS receiver designed for base station or reference station work is typically used. It should support required constellations, data formats, network communication and stable long-term operation."}]]}]
69:["$","h3","184",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Does CORS/VRS need mobile internet?"}]]}]
6a:["$","p","186",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Users normally access correction data through mobile data or other IP communication. Site network conditions should be checked before deployment."}]]}]
6b:["$","h2","188",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Conclusion"}]]}]
6c:["$","p","190",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Base-rover RTK and CORS/VRS are not competitors in every situation. They are different correction strategies for different project scales. Base-rover RTK is flexible and practical for local field work. CORS/VRS is more suitable for regional service, multiple users, continuous correction access and infrastructure-level applications."}]]}]
6d:["$","p","192",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"The right decision depends on coverage, number of users, accuracy requirements, communication conditions, installation resources and long-term operating goals. A professional supplier should help buyers evaluate these factors before recommending hardware or software."}]]}]
6e:["$","h2","194",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Final CTA"}]]}]
6f:["$","p","196",{"children":[["$","span","0",{"children":"Need help designing a GNSS correction setup? Share your project area, number of users, required accuracy and application scenario with TOKNAV. We can help evaluate whether base-rover RTK, CORS/VRS or a hybrid setup is the better choice."}]]}]
70:["$","p","198",{"children":[["$","strong","0",{"children":"CTA Button:"}],["$","span","1",{"children":" Contact Us"}]]}]
71:["$","p","199",{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Suggested Link: "}],["$","$L12",null,{"href":"/inquiry","children":"/inquiry"}]]}]
74:null
